snippet.title: The Secret Feud Between Prince Philip and The Queen Mother | Behind Closed Doors | Timeline
snippet.description:
The Coronation in 1953 appeared to be a glittering triumph for the House of Windsor. But behind the scenes there was a three-cornered story of jealousy and rivalry at the highest level.

On one side Prince Philip was at odds with the Queen Mother over his desire to modernise the monarchy. On the other the old Queen was jealous of her daughter's sudden rise to power. The Coronation was a critical year for the young Queen Elizabeth. She was preparing to undergo the most ancient and important royal ritual, but the two people closest to her, the Queen Mother and Prince Philip had very different ideas about how it should be handled. Philip, the dashing but dangerously modern consort, was anxious that the Coronation should not be simply a stuffy replay of previous reigns. He wanted 'some features relevant to the world today'. But he was fiercely resisted by the Queen Mother and by Princess Mary, who referred to Philip as 'the Hun'.

The new Queen was caught in the middle. In Coronation Coup, we learn that Mountbatten, who had engineered the marriage between Philip and Elizabeth wanted the family name changed to Windsor-Mountbatten after her accession. Also, while the new Queen largely sided with her mother over arrangements for the Coronation, she backed Philip over perhaps the most important decision to televise the ceremony inside Westminster Abbey. In doing so she set a precedent for television to be given access to the most intimate rituals.

snippet.title: The Bizarre Life Of Victoria's Disabled Grandson | Crippled Kaiser | Real Royalty
snippet.description:
Queen Victoria’s eldest child, Vicky, married the German Crown Prince in 1858. One year after her wedding Vicky endured a difficult birth that almost ended her life and left her baby, the future Kaiser Wilhelm II, with a permanently paralysed arm. Soon Vicky presided over a series of bizarre and often cruel attempts to cure Wilhelm of his disability. These included regular animal baths in which the body of a freshly slaughtered hare was wrapped around Wilhelm’s arm in the belief that its blood would bring life to his limb. These procedures created a highly dysfunctional relationship between Vicky and Wilhelm, he developed a growing hatred for his mother’s country while at the same time expressing his desire for ‘forbidden love’ with her.

snippet.title: The Glamorous Duchess Who Was A Third Wheel In Her OWN Marriage | PART 1 | Georgiana Cavendish
snippet.description:
Wealthy, noble, clever and pretty, Georgiana Spencer - later Cavendish - might have been seen to have it all. But like her indirect descendent Princess Diana many years later, Georgiana would end up in an unhappy and unfulfilling marriage, coping by gambling, drinking and partying to excess. snippet.title: The Lancastrian Mistress Who Became A Royal Wife | Katherine Swynford | Wars of the Roses
snippet.description:
Katherine Swynford was a woman who would defy the social norms of her age, and set in motion a tangle of events for the Wars of the Roses. Born a daughter of the gentry, she would have a real-life romance with John of Gaunt, the Duke of Lancaster, becoming his mistress for decades before finally - and shockingly for the time - becoming his wife. Their children, the Beauforts, would one day go on to claim the English throne through Henry VII...

snippet.title: The Survivor Who Was Mother To Two Kings | Cecily Neville | The Rose of Raby | Wars of the Roses
snippet.description:
How did the Wars of the Roses start - possibly with the ambitions of Richard Plantagenet, Duke of York. But by his side, throughout everything, was the backbone of the Yorkist cause - his wife, Cecily Neville, Duchess of York. She proved herself a fighter, a survivor, a mother and a grandmother, and committed to putting her dynasty on the throne. This video explores her life, her reasons, and the impact the 'Rose of Raby' had on the wars her husband started...

*Apologies within the video where I state that Elizabeth of York was Elizabeth Woodville's first child - I do in fact mean her first child with Edward IV! I also meant that Edward IV was the Duke of York's eldest LIVING son when he took the throne.*

snippet.title: From Yorkist Princess To Tudor Queen | Elizabeth Of York | The Wars of the Roses
snippet.description:
Henry VII may have ended the Wars of the Roses by taking the crown from Richard III on the battlefield at Bosworth, but he could never have held together the fragile peace England found in its wake without one woman - his wife and queen, Elizabeth of York. Elizabeth was a princess born to a new dynasty, destined to endure great tragedy and great joy, and to be the mother of yet another new dynasty, the Tudors. This video looks at Elizabeth's life and the obstacles she overcame to take her rightful place in England's history...

***Apologies for my error about Elizabeth Woodville's son - it was her younger son, Richard Grey, who was executed by Richard III, not her elder son Thomas Grey, as I've incorrectly stated. I am human and do sometimes make an error while recording!***
